/-!
# `IsLinearTopology` for `locTopology` (audit + minimal building block)

The single residual identified in `WedhornLocalizedTateData.lean`: the
`IsLinearTopology` instance for `(Localization.Away s, locTopology P T s
hopen)`, needed by `exists_dominating_unit_in_localization` (commit
`863aa86`).

## Audit

`locTopology` is generated by `locBasis`, a `RingSubgroupsBasis (locNhd
P T s)`. The basis sets `locNhd P T s n` are AddSubgroups of
`Localization.Away s`, NOT generally ideals: an element `d ‚ąą locNhd n`
is an image of `(locIdeal)^n ‚äÜ locSubring`, but `(1/s) ¬∑ d` may exit
`locSubring` (since `1/s` is not generally in `locSubring`).

For `IsLinearTopology B B`, we need a basis of OPEN IDEALS at 0
(equivalently, open submodules of `B` over `B`). Two natural attempts:

1. Use `locNhd P T s n` directly: fails because `locNhd n` is not an
   ideal of `Localization.Away s`.

2. Use `Submodule.span (Localization.Away s) (locNhd n : Set _)` (the
   ideal of `B` generated by `locNhd n`): this IS an ideal, AND is
   open (contains the open `locNhd n` and contains `0`). This file
   proves openness as the building block.

   The remaining structural step: showing these spans form a BASIS at
   `0`, i.e., `‚ąÄ open U ‚ąč 0, ‚ąÉ n, Submodule.span B (locNhd n) ‚äÜ U`.
   This requires more delicate analysis since `Submodule.span B (locNhd
   n)` includes `B`-multiples of `locNhd n`, which can be larger than
   `locNhd n`. Whether the spans shrink fast enough to fit inside an
   arbitrary `locNhd m` is the genuine analytic content.

## What this file provides

`locNhd_span_isOpen` ‚ÄĒ `Submodule.span (Localization.Away s) (locNhd P T
s n : Set _)` is an open subset of `Localization.Away s` under
`locTopology P T s hopen`. Direct from
`AddSubgroup.isOpen_of_mem_nhds`-style argument: the span contains the
open `locNhd n`, so it's a neighborhood of `0`, hence open (additive
subgroup in topological group).

## Single residual

```lean
theorem isLinearTopology_locTopology
    {A : Type*} [CommRing A] [TopologicalSpace A] [IsTopologicalRing A]
    (P : PairOfDefinition A) (T : Finset A) (s : A)
    (hopen : ‚ąÉ N : ‚Ąē, ‚ąÄ b : P.A‚āÄ, b ‚ąą P.I ^ N ‚Üí
      divByS (‚ÜĎb : A) s ‚ąą locSubring P T s) :
    @IsLinearTopology (Localization.Away s) (Localization.Away s) _ _ _
      (locTopology P T s hopen)
```

The proof would use `IsLinearTopology.mk` with the explicit submodule
basis `fun n => Submodule.span (Localization.Away s) (locNhd P T s n)`,
provided that:
* For each `n`, this submodule is open and in `nhds 0` (provided by
  this file's `locNhd_span_isOpen`).
* For each `U ‚ąą nhds 0`, ‚ąÉ `n` with `Submodule.span B (locNhd n) ‚äÜ U`
  (the structural shrinking property ‚ÄĒ the genuinely missing piece).

The shrinking property requires a careful analysis of how `B`-spans of
`locNhd n` decrease in `n`. For typical Tate-Huber setups this should
hold, but it requires a non-trivial computation: for any open `U
‚äá locNhd m`, find `n` such that `B ¬∑ locNhd n ‚äÜ locNhd m`. Equivalent
to: the `B`-action on `locNhd` is "tame" in the sense that finite
products with arbitrary `B`-elements eventually return to small
`locNhd`'s.

This is a structural-topological result on Wedhorn 8.1 localizations
and is the next concrete sub-target.

